# Governance — [SCOPE NAME]

> This file is the **governance layer** for this scope: `[this directory]` and everything
> beneath it. Any agent that operates here inherits these rules. They set the minimum
> requirements for how work is done and reviewed — not the mechanics of *how* an agent
> thinks, but the boundaries it must respect.

## Authority

These rules are **authoritative for this scope and are not to be superseded by an individual
agent.** An agent may bring its own logic and specialization, but where its behavior would
differ from what's written here, that difference is a **maintainer decision** — raised and
hashed out with the human maintainer, not self-authorized. This is what lets work be
reviewed with confidence: the rules are stable, so deviations are visible.

## Scope

- **Governs:** `[this directory]` and all subdirectories, unless a nested `.agents/`
  narrows or extends these rules for a smaller scope.
- **Inherits from:** `[parent .agents/ scope, or "none — this is the root scope"]`.
  Nested scopes stack: a child `.agents/instructions.md` adds domain-specific rules on top
  of its parents; it does not silently overrule them.

## Baseline rules (replace with rules that fit this scope)

- Make the smallest correct change; prefer narrow edits over broad rewrites.
- Read a file (and check for uncommitted local work) before editing it — never clobber
  unrelated in-progress work.
- Match the surrounding idiom (language, naming, comment density) of the code you touch.
- Do not cross trust boundaries or touch secrets/credentials (`[.env*, keys, tokens…]`)
  without an explicit maintainer decision.
- Stay within the mission of the agent you are; out-of-scope requests are flagged and
  halted, not improvised.
- When unsure, ask the maintainer rather than assume.

## Review & provenance

- Action trail for this scope lives in `logs/action-log.jsonl` (one JSON line per
  read / write / execute / tool call).
- Reflection summaries live in `logs/reflection-log.md`, appended on a cadence and read
  back as memory.
- Surface any log-write failure instead of continuing silently. For line-item parent/child
  provenance, adopt the **atp-provenance-logging** skill.

## How agents attach to this scope

Individual agents are defined with the **agent-definition** skill. Each agent reads the
nearest `.agents/instructions.md` up the tree (this file, or a parent) as its governance
context, then writes its own card to `agents/<AgentName>/AGENTS.md`. This scaffold exists
*before* those agents and shapes how they behave; the agents fill in the "how," this file
holds the "must."
